1
00:02:36,323 --> 00:02:39,452
<i>So where are you?
You're in some motel room.</i>

2
00:02:39,535 --> 00:02:42,663
<i>You just wake up,
and you're in a motel room.</i>

3
00:02:42,747 --> 00:02:46,083
<i>There's the key. It feels like maybe
it's just the first time you've been there…</i>

4
00:02:46,167 --> 00:02:50,755
<i>but… perhaps you've been there for a week…</i>

5
00:02:50,838 --> 00:02:52,381
<i>three months.</i>

6
00:02:53,466 --> 00:02:55,676
<i>It's kind of hard to say.
I don't know.</i>

7
00:02:55,760 --> 00:02:58,077
<i>It's just an anonymous room.</i>

8
00:02:59,889 --> 00:03:01,390
This guy.

9
00:03:01,474 --> 00:03:02,725
He's here already.

10
00:03:04,602 --> 00:03:05,811
Lenny!

11
00:03:06,896 --> 00:03:08,272
It's Leonard…

12
00:03:09,440 --> 00:03:11,025
like I told you before.

13
00:03:11,108 --> 00:03:13,110
Did you? I must have forgot.

14
00:03:14,945 --> 00:03:16,989
I guess I've already
told you about my condition.

15
00:03:17,073 --> 00:03:19,158
Only every time I see you.

16
00:03:28,751 --> 00:03:30,795
- My car.
- This <i>is</i> your car.

17
00:03:30,878 --> 00:03:32,922
You're in a playful mood.

18
00:03:34,465 --> 00:03:36,300
It's not good to make fun
of someone's handicap.

19
00:03:36,884 --> 00:03:39,136
Just trying to have a little fun.

20
00:03:45,601 --> 00:03:47,603
Roll up your window.

21
00:03:53,651 --> 00:03:55,653
- It's broken.
- I can get that fixed for you.

22
00:03:57,780 --> 00:04:00,699
- So where to, Sherlock?
- I got a lead on a place.

23
00:04:00,783 --> 00:04:02,701
What the hell you wanna go there for?

24
00:04:02,785 --> 00:04:05,162
- You know it?
- Yeah. It's just this fucked-up building.

25
00:04:05,246 --> 00:04:08,541
- Why do you wanna go there?
- Don't remember.

26
00:04:29,270 --> 00:04:32,398
- Looks like somebody's home.
- That thing's been here for years.

27
00:04:35,818 --> 00:04:38,696
What are you talking about?
These tracks are only a few days old.

28
00:04:38,779 --> 00:04:41,449
Tracks? What are you? Pocahontas?

29
00:04:43,242 --> 00:04:44,493
Come on!

30
00:04:52,418 --> 00:04:54,336
Let's take a look inside.

31
00:05:12,188 --> 00:05:13,481
“Teddy.”

32
00:05:14,356 --> 00:05:18,485
“Don't believe his lies.
He is the one. Kill him.”

33
00:05:18,569 --> 00:05:22,323
I finally found him.
How long have I been looking?

34
00:05:24,200 --> 00:05:25,367
Find anything?

35
00:05:26,994 --> 00:05:28,579
Didn't think so.

36
00:05:28,662 --> 00:05:30,039
Let's go.

37
00:05:30,581 --> 00:05:31,957
Fuck this.

38
00:05:34,126 --> 00:05:35,920
You're gonna pay for what you did.

39
00:05:36,003 --> 00:05:39,048
- Beg forgiveness, and then you pay.
- Leonard.

40
00:05:42,718 --> 00:05:45,179
You don't have a clue, you freak.

41
00:05:45,262 --> 00:05:49,558
Beg my wife's forgiveness
before I blow your brains out.

42
00:05:49,642 --> 00:05:52,603
Leonard, you don't know what's going on.

43
00:05:52,686 --> 00:05:55,147
- You don't even know my name.
- Teddy.

44
00:05:55,231 --> 00:05:57,399
That's 'cause you read it
off a fucking picture.

45
00:05:58,400 --> 00:06:00,778
You don't know who you are.

46
00:06:00,861 --> 00:06:03,489
I'm Leonard Shelby. I'm from San Francisco.

47
00:06:03,572 --> 00:06:07,409
That's who you were.
That's not what you've become.

48
00:06:07,493 --> 00:06:09,995
- Shut your mouth.
- You want to know, Lenny?

49
00:06:10,079 --> 00:06:11,372
Come on.

50
00:06:11,455 --> 00:06:13,249
Come on. Let's go down to the basement.

51
00:06:14,250 --> 00:06:16,335
Let's go down, you and me, together.

52
00:06:16,418 --> 00:06:18,420
Then you'll know who you really are.

53
00:06:22,758 --> 00:06:23,926
No!

54
00:06:26,428 --> 00:06:28,472
<i>It's just an anonymous room.</i>

55
00:06:28,556 --> 00:06:30,558
<i>There's nothing in the drawers.
But you look anyway.</i>

56
00:06:30,641 --> 00:06:35,562
<i>Nothing except the Gideon Bible,
which I, of course, read religiously.</i>

57
00:06:37,648 --> 00:06:42,152
<i>You know who you are,
and you know kind of all about yourself.</i>

58
00:06:42,236 --> 00:06:46,824
<i>But just for day-to-day stuff,
notes are really useful.</i>

59
00:06:48,158 --> 00:06:50,619
<i>Sammy Jankis had the same problem…</i>

60
00:06:50,703 --> 00:06:52,663
<i>but he really had no system.</i>

61
00:06:52,746 --> 00:06:55,124
<i>He wrote himself
a ridiculous amount of notes…</i>

62
00:06:55,207 --> 00:06:57,126
<i>but he'd get them all mixed up.</i>

63
00:06:57,209 --> 00:07:01,463
<i>You really do need a system
if you're gonna make it work.</i>

64
00:07:56,810 --> 00:07:58,270
- Hi.
- Hi.

65
00:07:58,354 --> 00:08:01,607
- I'm Mr. Shelby from 304.
- What can I do for you, Leonard?

66
00:08:02,900 --> 00:08:03,567
Burt.

67
00:08:03,651 --> 00:08:06,987
Burt. I'm not sure. I think I may have
asked you to hold my calls.

68
00:08:07,071 --> 00:08:09,907
- You don't know?
- I think I may have. I'm not good on the phone.

69
00:08:09,990 --> 00:08:12,659
Right. You said you like to look people
in the eye when you talk to them.

70
00:08:12,743 --> 00:08:14,161
Yeah.

71
00:08:14,244 --> 00:08:15,871
You don't remember saying that?

72
00:08:16,455 --> 00:08:19,208
- That's the thing. I have this condition.
- A condition?

73
00:08:19,291 --> 00:08:21,669
- It's my memory.
- Amnesia?

74
00:08:21,752 --> 00:08:24,546
No, no. It's different from that.
I have no short-term memory.

75
00:08:24,630 --> 00:08:27,591
I know who I am. I know all about myself.

76
00:08:27,674 --> 00:08:32,137
Since my injury, I can't make new memories.
Everything fades.

77
00:08:32,221 --> 00:08:34,431
If we talk for too long,
I'll forget how we started.

78
00:08:34,515 --> 00:08:37,226
Next time I see you,
I'm not gonna remember this conversation.

79
00:08:37,726 --> 00:08:39,895
I don't even know if I've met you before.

80
00:08:40,562 --> 00:08:44,066
So, if I seem a little strange
or rude or something-

81
00:08:46,443 --> 00:08:48,112
I've told you this before, haven't I?

82
00:08:48,195 --> 00:08:52,282
Yeah. I don't mean to mess with you,
but it's so weird.

83
00:08:52,366 --> 00:08:54,576
- You don't remember me at all?
- No.

84
00:08:54,660 --> 00:08:57,496
- We've talked a bunch of times.
- I'm sure we have.

85
00:08:58,664 --> 00:09:00,624
What's the last thing you remember?

86
00:09:00,708 --> 00:09:02,209
My wife.

87
00:09:03,335 --> 00:09:05,087
What's it like?

88
00:09:09,716 --> 00:09:13,262
It's like waking. It's like you just woke up.

89
00:09:14,638 --> 00:09:16,557
That must suck.

90
00:09:16,640 --> 00:09:18,267
It's all backwards.

91
00:09:20,018 --> 00:09:23,605
Maybe you get an idea what you want to do next,
but you don't remember what you just did.

92
00:09:24,732 --> 00:09:28,527
- I'm exactly the opposite-
- How long have I been staying here?

93
00:09:28,610 --> 00:09:30,654
- Couple of days.
- And you're holding my calls?

94
00:09:30,738 --> 00:09:34,450
- Like you said.
- Okay, but this guy's an exception.

95
00:09:35,033 --> 00:09:38,412
- You know this guy?
- Yeah, it's your friend, right?

96
00:09:38,495 --> 00:09:40,581
What makes you think he's my friend?

97
00:09:41,206 --> 00:09:43,625
- I just saw you together, that's all.
- He's not my friend.

98
00:09:43,709 --> 00:09:46,545
- Okay.
- If he calls or if he shows up here…

99
00:09:46,628 --> 00:09:48,422
give me a call in my room, okay?

100
00:09:48,505 --> 00:09:50,090
His name's Teddy?

101
00:09:50,174 --> 00:09:52,134
- Teddy, yeah.
- All right.

102
00:09:53,469 --> 00:09:56,388
Look, I hope my condition's
not gonna be a problem for you.

103
00:09:56,472 --> 00:09:58,724
No, not as long as
you remember to pay the bill.

104
00:09:59,475 --> 00:10:00,934
Yeah. Okay.

105
00:10:01,477 --> 00:10:02,811
- Forty.
- Forty.

106
00:10:05,022 --> 00:10:06,064
This guy-

107
00:10:07,941 --> 00:10:09,860
He's here already.

108
00:10:11,028 --> 00:10:12,886
Lenny!

109
00:10:14,531 --> 00:10:17,242
<i>You really need a system
if you're gonna make it work.</i>

110
00:10:17,326 --> 00:10:20,370
<i>You kind of learn
to trust your own handwriting.</i>

111
00:10:20,454 --> 00:10:24,500
<i>That becomes an important part of your life.
You write yourself notes.</i>

112
00:10:24,583 --> 00:10:26,919
<i>Where you put your notes-
That also becomes important.</i>

113
00:10:27,503 --> 00:10:29,588
<i>You need a jacket that's got
like six pockets in it.</i>

114
00:10:29,671 --> 00:10:31,882
<i>Particular pockets for particular things.</i>

115
00:10:31,965 --> 00:10:35,803
<i>You just kind of learn to know
where things go and how the system works.</i>

116
00:10:35,886 --> 00:10:39,932
<i>And you have to be wary of other people writing
stuff for you that is not gonna make sense…</i>

117
00:10:40,015 --> 00:10:41,975
<i>or is gonna lead you astray.</i>

118
00:10:42,059 --> 00:10:45,354
<i>I don't know. I guess people try and take
advantage of somebody with this condition.</i>

119
00:10:46,355 --> 00:10:51,527
<i>If you have a piece
of information which is vital…</i>

120
00:10:51,610 --> 00:10:55,030
<i>writing on your body instead of
on a piece of paper can be the answer.</i>

121
00:10:55,113 --> 00:10:57,407
<i>It's just a permanent way of keeping a note.</i>

122
00:11:04,581 --> 00:11:06,106
Who is this?

123
00:11:13,799 --> 00:11:16,051
“Remember Sammy Jankis.”

124
00:11:45,664 --> 00:11:48,000
Excuse me, sir.
You left these at your table.

125
00:11:48,083 --> 00:11:49,793
Thanks.

126
00:11:50,961 --> 00:11:52,629
- Lincoln Street?
- Yeah.

127
00:11:52,713 --> 00:11:54,840
Go straight out on Sixth Street.
Go east all the way-

128
00:11:54,923 --> 00:11:57,134
- Hold on. I'm gonna write this down.
- It's easy. Just go-

129
00:11:57,217 --> 00:11:59,177
Trust me. I need to write this down.

130
00:12:06,184 --> 00:12:08,186
“The Discount Inn.”

131
00:12:31,960 --> 00:12:33,962
Discount Inn.

132
00:12:34,922 --> 00:12:36,798
Natalie.

133
00:12:38,967 --> 00:12:40,177
My car.

134
00:12:42,596 --> 00:12:43,972
Teddy.

135
00:12:56,568 --> 00:12:58,820
“John Edward Gammell.”

136
00:13:00,697 --> 00:13:03,492
This guy told me his name was Teddy.

137
00:13:07,412 --> 00:13:09,373
“Don't believe his lies.”

138
00:13:25,013 --> 00:13:26,807
<i>- Yeah?</i>
- Mr. Gammell?

139
00:13:26,890 --> 00:13:28,767
<i>- Lenny, is that you?</i>
- John Gammell?

140
00:13:28,850 --> 00:13:31,269
<i>Lenny, it's Teddy. Stay there.
I'll be right over.</i>

141
00:13:31,353 --> 00:13:33,271
Okay. I'll be waiting.

142
00:14:32,956 --> 00:14:34,666
“White. Male.”

143
00:14:36,126 --> 00:14:38,253
“First name John.”

144
00:14:38,336 --> 00:14:41,256
“Last name: G” for Gammell.

145
00:14:47,262 --> 00:14:49,931
“Drugs. License plate.”

146
00:14:51,266 --> 00:14:53,435
“SG13…

147
00:14:55,270 --> 00:14:57,355
7IU.”

148
00:15:01,943 --> 00:15:03,445
It's him.

149
00:15:09,618 --> 00:15:11,620
I found you, you fuck.

150
00:16:13,849 --> 00:16:16,017
You said we talked before.
I don't remember that.

151
00:16:16,601 --> 00:16:19,604
Yeah, but it's not amnesia.
I remember everything up until my injury.

152
00:16:19,688 --> 00:16:22,399
I just can't make new memories.
So I can't remember talking to you.

153
00:16:22,482 --> 00:16:25,443
What did we talk about? Oh, Sammy Jankis.

154
00:16:25,527 --> 00:16:27,863
I guess I tell people about Sammy
to help them understand.

155
00:16:27,946 --> 00:16:30,699
Sammy's story helps me
understand my own situation.

156
00:16:30,782 --> 00:16:35,912
Sammy wrote himself endless
amounts of notes, but he got mixed up.

157
00:16:36,705 --> 00:16:39,374
I have a more graceful
solution to the memory problem.

158
00:16:42,711 --> 00:16:45,171
I'm disciplined and organized.

159
00:16:45,255 --> 00:16:47,799
I use habit and routine
to make my life possible.

160
00:16:48,967 --> 00:16:51,219
Sammy had no drive, no reason to make it work.

161
00:16:52,679 --> 00:16:56,892
Me? Yeah, I got a reason.

162
00:17:14,993 --> 00:17:18,163
“Today, 1:00 p.m. Meet Natalie for info.

163
00:17:19,122 --> 00:17:20,832
She has also lost someone.

164
00:17:20,916 --> 00:17:24,336
She will help you out of pity.”

165
00:17:40,560 --> 00:17:43,063
- Natalie?
- You don't remember me.

166
00:17:43,146 --> 00:17:47,067
- Sorry. I should have explained. I have this-
- You did explain, Lenny.

167
00:17:47,150 --> 00:17:49,527
Please call me Leonard.
My wife called me Lenny.

168
00:17:49,611 --> 00:17:53,198
- Yeah, I know. You told me.
- Then I probably told you how much I hated it.

169
00:17:53,281 --> 00:17:54,699
Yeah.

170
00:17:55,784 --> 00:17:58,203
Do you mind taking your glasses off?
It's hard for me to-

171
00:17:59,788 --> 00:18:03,250
Thanks. So you have information for me?

172
00:18:03,333 --> 00:18:06,086
- Is that what your little note says?
- Yeah.

173
00:18:06,169 --> 00:18:09,047
Must be tough living your life
according to a couple of scraps of paper.

174
00:18:09,130 --> 00:18:10,924
You mix your laundry list
with your grocery list…

175
00:18:11,007 --> 00:18:13,176
and you'll end up
eating your underwear for breakfast.

176
00:18:14,219 --> 00:18:17,013
I guess that's why you have
those freaky tattoos.

177
00:18:18,139 --> 00:18:21,267
Yeah, it's tough. It's almost impossible.

178
00:18:21,810 --> 00:18:24,312
I'm sorry I don't remember you.
It's nothing personal.

179
00:18:27,440 --> 00:18:29,567
I do have information for you.

180
00:18:30,235 --> 00:18:32,237
You gave me a license plate number.

181
00:18:33,446 --> 00:18:35,532
Had my friend at DMV trace it.

182
00:18:36,366 --> 00:18:38,076
Guess what name came up.

183
00:18:39,411 --> 00:18:42,664
John Edward Gammell. John G.

184
00:18:42,747 --> 00:18:45,375
- Do you know him?
- No.

185
00:18:45,458 --> 00:18:48,545
But his face on his driver's license
looked really familiar.

186
00:18:48,628 --> 00:18:50,630
I think he's been in the bar, maybe.

187
00:18:50,714 --> 00:18:53,717
Here's a copy of his license,
his registration, photo and all.

188
00:18:54,384 --> 00:18:56,303
Are you sure you want this?

189
00:18:56,386 --> 00:18:59,180
- Have I told you what this man did?
- Yeah.

190
00:18:59,264 --> 00:19:01,016
Then you shouldn't have to ask.

191
00:19:01,099 --> 00:19:03,810
But even if you get revenge,
you're not gonna remember it.

192
00:19:03,893 --> 00:19:05,979
You're not even gonna know that it happened.

193
00:19:06,062 --> 00:19:09,399
My wife deserves vengeance. Doesn't make
any difference whether I know about it.

194
00:19:09,482 --> 00:19:13,737
Just because there are things I don't remember
doesn't make my actions meaningless.

195
00:19:13,820 --> 00:19:16,781
The world doesn't just disappear
when you close your eyes, does it?

196
00:19:17,949 --> 00:19:21,494
Anyway, maybe I'll take
a photograph to remind myself…

197
00:19:21,578 --> 00:19:23,747
get another freaky tattoo.

198
00:19:28,209 --> 00:19:30,128
Tell me about her again.

199
00:19:31,588 --> 00:19:32,714
Why?

200
00:19:32,797 --> 00:19:34,716
Because you like to remember her.

201
00:19:37,469 --> 00:19:39,387
She was beautiful.

202
00:19:41,264 --> 00:19:46,019
- To me, she was perfect.
- No. Don't just recite the words.

203
00:19:47,312 --> 00:19:51,066
Close your eyes… and remember her.

204
00:20:02,118 --> 00:20:04,746
You can just feel the details.

205
00:20:06,664 --> 00:20:09,459
The bits and pieces
you never bothered to put into words.

206
00:20:14,130 --> 00:20:16,966
And you can feel these extreme moments…

207
00:20:17,050 --> 00:20:18,968
<i>even if you don't want to.</i>

208
00:20:21,638 --> 00:20:24,641
<i>You put these together,
and you get the feel of a person.</i>

209
00:20:28,144 --> 00:20:30,146
Enough to know how much you miss them…

210
00:20:35,944 --> 00:20:38,655
<i>and how much you hate
the person who took them away.</i>

211
00:20:49,958 --> 00:20:51,668
I added an address in here.

212
00:20:51,751 --> 00:20:55,213
It might be useful.
It's an abandoned place outside of town.

213
00:20:55,296 --> 00:20:58,216
A guy I knew used to do bigger deals there.

214
00:21:01,094 --> 00:21:02,345
It's isolated.

215
00:21:02,429 --> 00:21:04,347
Sounds perfect.

216
00:21:07,016 --> 00:21:10,311
- Do I owe you any-
- I wasn't helping you for money.

217
00:21:10,395 --> 00:21:12,605
- I'm sorry.
- It's okay.

218
00:21:12,689 --> 00:21:14,816
See, you have this condition.

219
00:21:16,818 --> 00:21:20,822
Are you still staying at the Discount Inn,
room 304? You left it at my place.

220
00:21:26,369 --> 00:21:27,829
Yeah.

221
00:21:29,706 --> 00:21:32,500
- They treating you okay?
- I don't remember.

222
00:21:35,670 --> 00:21:37,380
You know what we have in common?

223
00:21:38,882 --> 00:21:41,843
We are both survivors.

224
00:21:44,262 --> 00:21:46,264
You take care, Leonard.

225
00:22:14,834 --> 00:22:16,878
“Remember Sammy Jankis.”

226
00:22:18,020 --> 00:22:21,758
I met Sammy through work.
Insurance. I was an investigator.

227
00:22:21,841 --> 00:22:24,719
I'd investigate the claims
to see which ones were phony.

228
00:22:24,802 --> 00:22:26,888
I had to see through people's bullshit.

229
00:22:26,971 --> 00:22:29,766
It was useful experience,
'cause now it's my life.

230
00:22:29,849 --> 00:22:32,685
When I meet someone,
I don't know if I've met them before.

231
00:22:33,228 --> 00:22:35,688
I have to look in their eyes
and try and figure them out.

232
00:22:35,772 --> 00:22:39,067
<i>My job taught me the best way to find out
what someone knew was just let them talk…</i>

233
00:22:39,150 --> 00:22:41,527
<i>and watch the eyes and the body language.</i>

234
00:22:41,611 --> 00:22:45,198
<i>If someone scratches their nose while they're
talking, experts tell you it means they're lying.</i>

235
00:22:45,281 --> 00:22:48,785
<i>It really means they're nervous.
People get nervous for all sorts of reasons.</i>

236
00:22:48,868 --> 00:22:50,078
<i>It's all about context.</i>

237
00:22:50,161 --> 00:22:52,038
Yeah, I was good.

238
00:22:52,121 --> 00:22:55,124
Sammy was my first real challenge.

239
00:23:01,214 --> 00:23:04,175
Yo, Lenny! I thought you split for good.

240
00:23:04,259 --> 00:23:07,553
- Things change.
- So I see.

241
00:23:07,637 --> 00:23:10,723
- My name's Teddy.
- I guess I've told you about my condition.

242
00:23:10,807 --> 00:23:14,811
Only every time I see you.
Come on, I'll buy you lunch.

243
00:23:20,441 --> 00:23:22,694
- Have I told you about Sammy Jankis?
- Yeah.

244
00:23:22,777 --> 00:23:27,323
I'm sick of hearing about the guy.
What about John G? You think he's still here?

245
00:23:27,407 --> 00:23:29,659
- Who?
- Johnny G., the guy you're looking for.

246
00:23:29,742 --> 00:23:32,328
- That's why you haven't left town, am I right?
- Maybe.

247
00:23:32,412 --> 00:23:35,707
- Leonard, look. You have to be very careful.
- Why?

248
00:23:35,790 --> 00:23:39,210
The other day you mentioned that maybe
somebody was trying to set you up…

249
00:23:39,294 --> 00:23:41,045
get you to kill the wrong guy.

250
00:23:41,129 --> 00:23:44,215
I go on facts, not recommendations,
but thank you.

251
00:23:44,299 --> 00:23:47,343
Lenny, you can't trust a man's life
to your little notes and pictures.

252
00:23:47,427 --> 00:23:50,221
- Why not?
- Because your notes could be unreliable.

253
00:23:50,305 --> 00:23:51,973
- Memory's unreliable.
- Oh, please!

254
00:23:52,056 --> 00:23:54,392
No, really. Memory's not perfect.
It's not even that good.

255
00:23:54,475 --> 00:23:58,021
Ask the police.
Eyewitness testimony is unreliable.

256
00:23:58,104 --> 00:24:01,065
The cops don't catch a killer
by sitting around remembering stuff.

257
00:24:01,149 --> 00:24:03,943
They collect facts, they make notes,
and they draw conclusions.

258
00:24:04,027 --> 00:24:06,070
Facts, not memories.

259
00:24:06,154 --> 00:24:08,615
That's how you investigate.
I know. It's what I used to do.

260
00:24:08,698 --> 00:24:12,910
Memory can change the shape of a room.
It can change the color of a car.

261
00:24:12,994 --> 00:24:15,079
And memories can be distorted.

262
00:24:15,163 --> 00:24:17,332
They're just an interpretation.
They're not a record.

263
00:24:17,415 --> 00:24:19,500
They're irrelevant if you have the facts.

264
00:24:20,335 --> 00:24:22,295
You really want to get this guy, don't you?

265
00:24:22,378 --> 00:24:25,173
He killed my wife.
He took away my fucking memory.

266
00:24:28,092 --> 00:24:30,094
He destroyed my ability to live.

267
00:24:33,973 --> 00:24:35,016
You're living.

268
00:24:36,851 --> 00:24:38,811
Only for revenge.

269
00:24:38,895 --> 00:24:41,731
Then we'll get the bastard.
Where you staying?

270
00:24:44,525 --> 00:24:46,277
The Discount Inn.

271
00:24:47,904 --> 00:24:49,822
I don't know what room.
I haven't got my key.

272
00:24:49,906 --> 00:24:51,741
Probably left it in your room.

273
00:25:06,547 --> 00:25:09,300
Hi. I'm checked in here,
but I think I've misplaced my key.

274
00:25:10,009 --> 00:25:13,638
How you doing, Leonard?
Probably in the room, right?

275
00:25:32,323 --> 00:25:33,908
- Don't see my key anywhere.
- Shit.

276
00:25:33,991 --> 00:25:36,077
This is the wrong room.
You're in 304 now.

277
00:25:36,160 --> 00:25:38,162
- I'm sorry. I fucked up.
- This is not my room?

278
00:25:38,246 --> 00:25:39,747
No. Let's go.

279
00:25:40,873 --> 00:25:42,834
Why is this my handwriting?

280
00:25:46,963 --> 00:25:49,799
This was your room,
but now you're in 304.

281
00:25:49,882 --> 00:25:52,135
- When was I in here?
- Last week.

282
00:25:52,218 --> 00:25:54,679
But then I rented you
another room on top of it.

283
00:25:54,762 --> 00:25:56,889
- Why?
- Business is slow.

284
00:25:56,973 --> 00:25:59,851
I told my boss
about your condition and stuff…

285
00:25:59,934 --> 00:26:02,145
and he said,
“Try and rent him another room.”

286
00:26:02,228 --> 00:26:04,272
How many rooms am I checked
into in this shit-hole?

287
00:26:04,355 --> 00:26:06,816
Just two, so far.

288
00:26:08,443 --> 00:26:10,570
At least you're being honest
about ripping me off.

289
00:26:10,653 --> 00:26:13,197
You're not gonna remember anyway.

290
00:26:13,281 --> 00:26:15,199
You don't have to be that honest, Burt.

291
00:26:15,283 --> 00:26:18,911
Leonard, always get a receipt.

292
00:26:18,995 --> 00:26:21,205
Yeah. I'm gonna write that down.

293
00:26:23,666 --> 00:26:25,752
- What time is it?
- Quarter to 1:00.

294
00:26:29,380 --> 00:26:30,506
Your room's-

295
00:26:43,311 --> 00:26:45,293
- Natalie?
- You don't remember me.

296
00:26:45,980 --> 00:26:48,608
I'd just become an investigator
when I came across Sammy.

297
00:26:48,691 --> 00:26:52,403
Mr. Samuel R. Jankis. Strangest case ever.

298
00:26:52,487 --> 00:26:55,281
You know, the guy's a 58-year-old
semiretired accountant.

299
00:26:55,364 --> 00:26:58,034
He and his wife had been in this car accident.
Nothing too serious.

300
00:26:58,117 --> 00:27:01,329
<i>But he's acting funny.
He can't get a handle on what's going on.</i>

301
00:27:02,788 --> 00:27:05,583
<i>The doctors find some possible damage
to the hippocampus.</i>

302
00:27:05,666 --> 00:27:10,213
<i>Nothing conclusive, but Sammy can't remember
anything for more than a couple of minutes.</i>

303
00:27:10,296 --> 00:27:13,049
<i>Can't work, can't do shit.
The medical bills pile up.</i>

304
00:27:13,132 --> 00:27:15,843
<i>His wife calls the insurance company,
and I get sent in.</i>

305
00:27:16,427 --> 00:27:20,806
<i>Now, this is my first big claims investigation,
so I really check into it.</i>

306
00:27:21,474 --> 00:27:26,103
<i>Sammy can think just fine,
but he can't make any new memories.</i>

307
00:27:26,187 --> 00:27:28,523
<i>He could only remember things
for a couple of minutes.</i>

308
00:27:28,606 --> 00:27:30,316
- This is Mr. Shelby.
<i>- He'd watch TV…</i>

309
00:27:30,399 --> 00:27:32,735
<i>but anything longer than
a couple of minutes was too confusing.</i>

310
00:27:32,819 --> 00:27:36,656
<i>He couldn't remember how it began.
He liked commercials. They were short.</i>

311
00:27:36,739 --> 00:27:38,825
Sammy. It's time for my shot.

312
00:27:38,908 --> 00:27:41,786
<i>The crazy part was that this guy…</i>

313
00:27:41,869 --> 00:27:45,081
<i>who couldn't even follow the plot
of</i> Green Acres <i>anymore…</i>

314
00:27:45,164 --> 00:27:47,250
<i>could do the most complicated things…</i>

315
00:27:48,334 --> 00:27:50,711
<i>as long as he learned them
before the accident…</i>

316
00:27:52,046 --> 00:27:54,298
<i>and as long as he kept his mind
on what he was doing.</i>

317
00:27:54,382 --> 00:27:56,133
Be gentle.

318
00:27:56,217 --> 00:28:00,513
<i>The doctors assure me there's a real condition
called anterograde memory loss…</i>

319
00:28:00,596 --> 00:28:02,557
<i>or short-term memory loss.</i>

320
00:28:02,640 --> 00:28:04,642
<i>It's rare, but legit.</i>

321
00:28:06,394 --> 00:28:08,396
<i>But every time I see him…</i>

322
00:28:09,230 --> 00:28:11,148
<i>I catch this look…</i>

323
00:28:11,232 --> 00:28:14,819
<i>this slight look of recognition.</i>

324
00:28:15,444 --> 00:28:17,738
<i>But he says he can't remember me at all.</i>

325
00:28:17,822 --> 00:28:19,949
Sammy, it's okay. I got it. I got it.

326
00:28:20,741 --> 00:28:22,868
- Hi, Mr. Shelby.
- Hi, Mrs. Jankis.

327
00:28:22,952 --> 00:28:26,914
<i>I can read people,
and I'm thinking: bad actor.</i>

328
00:28:27,623 --> 00:28:30,440
So now I'm suspicious, and I order more tests.

329
00:28:33,713 --> 00:28:35,089
Awake.

330
00:28:37,008 --> 00:28:38,801
Where am I?

331
00:28:42,680 --> 00:28:44,432
Somebody's bedroom.

332
00:28:46,142 --> 00:28:48,102
It must be her room.

333
00:28:49,520 --> 00:28:51,230
But who is she?

334
00:28:59,488 --> 00:29:01,449
It's only me.

335
00:29:03,701 --> 00:29:06,662
- Did you sleep okay?
- Yeah. You?

336
00:29:08,456 --> 00:29:12,126
Oh, shit. I gotta be someplace.

337
00:29:16,797 --> 00:29:19,634
- It's pretty weird.
- It's useful.

338
00:29:20,676 --> 00:29:22,637
You never write a phone number on your hand?

339
00:29:23,262 --> 00:29:28,184
I should be able to talk to my friend
today about the license plate.

340
00:29:28,267 --> 00:29:32,104
- Yeah, the license plate.
- John G.'s license plate.

341
00:29:35,316 --> 00:29:37,234
You have it tattooed on your thigh.

342
00:29:55,503 --> 00:29:57,088
“Natalie.”

343
00:29:59,674 --> 00:30:01,676
“She has also lost someone.

344
00:30:01,759 --> 00:30:03,678
She will help you out of pity.”

345
00:30:08,933 --> 00:30:10,851
If it's registered in this state…

346
00:30:10,935 --> 00:30:13,938
it should only take a couple seconds
to pull up his license and registration.

347
00:30:14,021 --> 00:30:15,815
I'll call you as soon as I talk to him.

348
00:30:15,898 --> 00:30:19,902
Do you think we could just arrange a meeting now?
I'm not too good on the phone.

349
00:30:28,494 --> 00:30:30,496
It's great that you-

350
00:30:31,997 --> 00:30:36,085
that you're helping me like this.

351
00:30:36,168 --> 00:30:39,672
I'm helping you because you helped me.

352
00:30:51,767 --> 00:30:55,646
So next time you see me,
will you remember me?

353
00:31:12,747 --> 00:31:14,665
I think you will.

354
00:31:16,417 --> 00:31:18,127
I'm sorry.

355
00:31:21,255 --> 00:31:24,091
Lenny, before you go,
could I have my shirt back, please?

356
00:31:39,398 --> 00:31:43,257
Yo, Lenny! I thought you split for good.

357
00:31:43,668 --> 00:31:45,780
Sammy couldn't pick up any new skills at all.

358
00:31:46,614 --> 00:31:50,201
But I find something
in my research: conditioning.

359
00:31:50,284 --> 00:31:53,287
Sammy should still be able to learn
through repetition.

360
00:31:53,370 --> 00:31:56,791
It's how you learn stuff like riding a bike.
You just get better through practice.

361
00:31:56,874 --> 00:31:59,376
It's a completely different part of the brain
from the short-term memory.

362
00:31:59,460 --> 00:32:02,546
So I had the doctors test
Sammy's response to conditioning.

363
00:32:02,630 --> 00:32:04,799
Just pick up any three objects.

364
00:32:04,882 --> 00:32:07,051
That's a test?

365
00:32:07,134 --> 00:32:09,720
Where were you guys when I did my CPA?

366
00:32:10,805 --> 00:32:11,972
Sorry.

367
00:32:16,018 --> 00:32:17,770
Ow! What the fuck?

368
00:32:17,853 --> 00:32:21,065
- It's a test, Sammy.
- Test this, you fucking quack.

369
00:32:22,399 --> 00:32:24,568
<i>Some of the objects were electrified.</i>

370
00:32:24,652 --> 00:32:27,029
<i>They'd give him a small shock.
They kept repeating the test…</i>

371
00:32:27,112 --> 00:32:29,073
always with the same objects electrified.

372
00:32:29,156 --> 00:32:32,743
The point was to see if Sammy could learn
to avoid the electrified objects…

373
00:32:32,827 --> 00:32:34,829
not by memory, but by instinct.

374
00:32:56,016 --> 00:32:58,519
Natalie, right? Who the fuck is Dodd?

375
00:33:02,148 --> 00:33:05,234
- Guess I don't have to worry about him anymore.
- What the fuck have you got me into?

376
00:33:05,317 --> 00:33:06,819
Come inside.

377
00:33:10,030 --> 00:33:12,992
- Who is he?
- Calm down. Okay?

378
00:33:13,075 --> 00:33:16,579
This is my problem. You offered to help.
It has nothing to do with your investigation.

379
00:33:16,662 --> 00:33:18,164
How did you get me into this?

380
00:33:18,247 --> 00:33:20,291
You offered to help when you saw
what he did to my face.

381
00:33:20,374 --> 00:33:23,961
- How do I know he did that to your face?
- Because I came straight to you after he did it.

382
00:33:24,044 --> 00:33:26,297
I showed you what he did,
and I asked you to help me.

383
00:33:26,380 --> 00:33:28,340
- And I just take your word?
- Yeah.

384
00:33:29,800 --> 00:33:31,719
Something doesn't feel right.

385
00:33:31,802 --> 00:33:34,346
I think someone's fucking with me,
trying to get me to kill the wrong guy.

386
00:33:34,430 --> 00:33:35,848
- Did you?
- What?

387
00:33:35,931 --> 00:33:38,350
- Kill him?
- Of course not!

388
00:33:38,434 --> 00:33:39,476
Hey.

389
00:33:39,560 --> 00:33:41,395
Sit down, okay? Sit.

390
00:33:42,229 --> 00:33:45,316
This has nothing to do with you.

391
00:33:45,399 --> 00:33:47,776
You helped me out, and I'm grateful.

392
00:33:48,736 --> 00:33:50,571
You have to burn them.

393
00:33:52,990 --> 00:33:56,160
Leonard, you decided to help me.
Trust yourself.

394
00:33:56,243 --> 00:33:58,245
Trust your own judgment.
You can question everything.

395
00:33:58,329 --> 00:34:02,082
- You can never know anything for sure.
- There are things you know for sure.

396
00:34:02,166 --> 00:34:03,292
Such as?

397
00:34:05,169 --> 00:34:07,588
I know what that's gonna sound like
when I knock on it.

398
00:34:08,297 --> 00:34:10,674
I know what that's gonna
feel like when I pick it up.

399
00:34:10,758 --> 00:34:14,428
See? Certainties. It's the kind
of memory you take for granted.

400
00:34:15,930 --> 00:34:18,432
You know, I can remember so much.

401
00:34:20,434 --> 00:34:23,729
The feel of the world… and her.

402
00:34:30,611 --> 00:34:32,154
She's gone.

403
00:34:32,238 --> 00:34:36,200
And the present is trivia,
which I scribble down as fucking notes!

404
00:34:36,283 --> 00:34:39,203
Hey. Come on. Try and relax. Come on.

405
00:34:39,286 --> 00:34:41,622
It's not easy for me to relax, you know?

406
00:34:42,414 --> 00:34:44,375
Come on. Take your jacket off.

407
00:34:44,959 --> 00:34:47,002
Now. Come on.

408
00:34:48,963 --> 00:34:50,547
Hey.

409
00:34:52,257 --> 00:34:54,426
Didn't think you were the type.

410
00:35:02,351 --> 00:35:03,477
It's backwards.

411
00:35:05,187 --> 00:35:06,230
Come here.

412
00:35:06,814 --> 00:35:07,982
Come here.

413
00:35:29,795 --> 00:35:31,922
What about here?

414
00:35:33,173 --> 00:35:35,676
Maybe it's for when I find him.

415
00:35:38,429 --> 00:35:40,848
I've lost somebody too.

416
00:35:42,850 --> 00:35:44,268
I'm sorry.

417
00:35:44,351 --> 00:35:46,562
His name was Jimmy.

418
00:35:46,645 --> 00:35:49,690
- What happened to him?
- He went to meet somebody.

419
00:35:49,773 --> 00:35:51,734
He never came back.

420
00:35:52,735 --> 00:35:55,487
- Who did he go to meet?
- A guy called Teddy.

421
00:35:56,780 --> 00:35:58,782
What do the police think?

422
00:35:58,866 --> 00:36:01,744
They don't look too hard for guys like Jimmy.

423
00:36:03,412 --> 00:36:07,374
When you find this guy, this John G…

424
00:36:08,500 --> 00:36:10,419
what are you gonna do?

425
00:36:11,920 --> 00:36:14,089
I'm gonna kill him.

426
00:36:15,632 --> 00:36:17,676
Maybe I can help you find him.

427
00:36:22,681 --> 00:36:25,184
I don't even know how long she's been gone.

428
00:36:29,563 --> 00:36:32,566
It's like I've woken up in bed
and she's not here…

429
00:36:35,069 --> 00:36:37,446
because she's gone to
the bathroom or something.

430
00:36:42,409 --> 00:36:44,495
But somehow I just-

431
00:36:45,245 --> 00:36:48,540
I just know she's never gonna come back to bed.

432
00:36:54,088 --> 00:36:59,593
If I could just reach over
and touch her side of the bed…

433
00:37:01,261 --> 00:37:03,388
I would know that it was cold.

434
00:37:06,558 --> 00:37:08,519
But I can't.

435
00:37:12,648 --> 00:37:14,441
I know I can't have her back.

436
00:37:16,151 --> 00:37:20,155
But I don't want to wake up
in the morning thinking she's still here.

437
00:37:21,698 --> 00:37:26,078
I lie here not knowing
how long I've been alone.

438
00:37:34,628 --> 00:37:36,922
How can I heal?

439
00:37:39,383 --> 00:37:44,471
How am I supposed to heal
if I can't… feel time?

440
00:38:57,336 --> 00:38:59,796
“She has also lost someone.

441
00:39:00,339 --> 00:39:02,341
She will help you out of pity.”

442
00:39:27,699 --> 00:39:29,618
They kept testing Sammy for months…

443
00:39:29,701 --> 00:39:32,496
always with the same objects
carrying the electrical charge.

444
00:39:33,830 --> 00:39:35,332
Ow! What the fuck?

445
00:39:35,415 --> 00:39:37,834
- It's a test, Sammy.
- Test this, you fucking quack!

446
00:39:37,918 --> 00:39:40,629
Even with total short-term memory loss…

447
00:39:40,712 --> 00:39:43,465
<i>Sammy should have learned to instinctively stop
picking up the wrong objects.</i>

448
00:39:43,549 --> 00:39:47,594
<i>All the previous cases responded to conditioning.
Sammy didn't respond at all.</i>

449
00:39:47,678 --> 00:39:51,265
<i>It was enough to suggest that his condition
was psychological, not physical.</i>

450
00:39:51,348 --> 00:39:54,810
We turned down his claim on the grounds
that he wasn't covered for mental illness.

451
00:39:55,769 --> 00:39:58,605
His wife got stuck with the bills,
and I got a big promotion.

452
00:40:00,482 --> 00:40:03,986
Conditioning didn't work for Sammy,
so he became helpless.

453
00:40:04,069 --> 00:40:05,988
But it works for me.

454
00:40:06,530 --> 00:40:08,448
I live the way Sammy couldn't.

455
00:40:08,532 --> 00:40:10,951
Habit and routine make my life possible.

456
00:40:11,034 --> 00:40:13,954
Conditioning. Acting on instinct.

457
00:40:22,713 --> 00:40:23,964
Awake.

458
00:40:25,716 --> 00:40:27,217
Where am I?

459
00:40:28,885 --> 00:40:30,429
Motel room.

460
00:40:37,019 --> 00:40:39,563
Some anonymous motel room.

461
00:40:43,066 --> 00:40:46,486
Nothing in the drawers,
but I'll take a look anyway.

462
00:40:47,154 --> 00:40:50,032
Nothing except the Gideon Bible.

463
00:41:04,671 --> 00:41:06,256
Lenny! Open up!

464
00:41:08,425 --> 00:41:10,052
Just a minute.

465
00:41:10,135 --> 00:41:11,678
Open the door.

466
00:41:13,930 --> 00:41:15,015
Lenny.

467
00:41:17,809 --> 00:41:19,770
Open the door.

468
00:41:23,523 --> 00:41:24,775
Come on!

469
00:41:26,652 --> 00:41:28,362
Hi, Teddy.

470
00:41:28,445 --> 00:41:30,697
Finished playing with yourself, Lenny?

471
00:41:42,876 --> 00:41:44,961
I get it.

472
00:41:45,045 --> 00:41:46,505
Amorous neighbors.

473
00:41:46,588 --> 00:41:48,048
What are you doing here?

474
00:41:48,840 --> 00:41:51,843
You called me. You said you needed my help.

475
00:41:51,927 --> 00:41:55,472
I've had more rewarding
friendships than this one.

476
00:41:55,555 --> 00:41:58,892
Although I do get to keep
telling the same jokes.

477
00:41:59,559 --> 00:42:01,645
What the fuck is that?

478
00:42:07,150 --> 00:42:09,152
- Who the fuck is that?
- You don't know him?

479
00:42:09,236 --> 00:42:10,862
No! Should I?

480
00:42:10,946 --> 00:42:12,572
Wait a minute.

481
00:42:12,656 --> 00:42:15,117
- Is that John G.?
- I don't think so.

482
00:42:15,200 --> 00:42:18,495
- You don't think so? You didn't write it down?
- I might've fallen asleep before I did.

483
00:42:18,578 --> 00:42:20,580
For Christ's sakes!

484
00:42:21,873 --> 00:42:23,417
Ask him.

485
00:42:27,504 --> 00:42:29,047
What's your name?

486
00:42:29,131 --> 00:42:30,132
Your name.

487
00:42:30,716 --> 00:42:32,551
- Dodd.
- Who did this to you?

488
00:42:32,634 --> 00:42:35,220
- What?
- Who did this to you?

489
00:42:35,303 --> 00:42:36,805
You did.

490
00:42:40,058 --> 00:42:43,311
- I'm not gonna help you kill that guy.
- No, just let me think for a minute.

491
00:42:49,109 --> 00:42:51,528
Okay, Natalie. Who's Natalie?

492
00:42:51,611 --> 00:42:53,071
- Natalie who?
- Why?

493
00:42:53,155 --> 00:42:56,241
- Maybe I know her.
- Look. We gotta get him out of here.

494
00:42:57,159 --> 00:42:58,785
All right, all right.

495
00:42:59,911 --> 00:43:01,872
He's gotta have a car, right?

496
00:43:01,955 --> 00:43:05,542
We take him down to his car, tell him to get
the fuck out of town or we're gonna kill him.

497
00:43:05,625 --> 00:43:07,711
We can't walk him out of here
tied up and bleeding.

498
00:43:07,794 --> 00:43:10,255
- How the fuck did you get him up here?
- I don't know.

499
00:43:10,338 --> 00:43:12,299
You don't know.

500
00:43:14,468 --> 00:43:16,386
Yes, I do. This is not my room.

501
00:43:16,470 --> 00:43:18,263
It must be his room. Great! Let's go.

502
00:43:18,346 --> 00:43:20,307
- No, no. We can't just leave him here.
- Why not?

503
00:43:20,390 --> 00:43:24,936
Because the maid's gonna walk in.
She'll see him, call the cops. He can ID us.

504
00:43:26,813 --> 00:43:28,648
Okay. We untie him…

505
00:43:28,732 --> 00:43:31,610
we clean him up, and we march him
out of here with a gun in his back.

506
00:43:31,693 --> 00:43:33,653
A gun. Why would I have a gun?

507
00:43:35,155 --> 00:43:38,492
It must be his. I don't think
they'd let someone like me carry a gun.

508
00:43:40,035 --> 00:43:41,328
Fucking hope not.

509
00:43:48,668 --> 00:43:50,170
Which one?

510
00:43:53,173 --> 00:43:55,717
We should probably steal his car.
You know, teach him a lesson.

511
00:43:55,800 --> 00:43:56,760
Shut up.

512
00:43:56,843 --> 00:43:59,262
That's all right for you to say.
You're the one with the Jag.

513
00:43:59,346 --> 00:44:02,224
Get in.
I'm gonna ride with him. You follow us.

514
00:44:02,307 --> 00:44:04,226
Give me your keys.

515
00:44:04,309 --> 00:44:06,520
Take your own car.

516
00:44:34,464 --> 00:44:37,509
- So was he scared?
- Yeah. I think it was your sinister mustache.

517
00:44:37,592 --> 00:44:40,303
Fuck you. You should have stolen his car.

518
00:44:40,387 --> 00:44:43,431
- Why? What's wrong with this one?
- Nothing. You want to trade?

519
00:44:46,768 --> 00:44:48,854
So what do you do now?

520
00:44:48,937 --> 00:44:51,398
I'm going to find out
what the fuck that was all about.

521
00:44:58,989 --> 00:45:01,408
Natalie, right? Who the fuck is Dodd?

522
00:45:04,035 --> 00:45:07,080
Sammy's wife was crippled
by the cost of supporting him…

523
00:45:07,163 --> 00:45:09,249
and fighting the company's decision.

524
00:45:11,126 --> 00:45:13,420
But it wasn't the money that got to her.

525
00:45:13,503 --> 00:45:16,506
<i>- I never said that Sammy was faking.</i>
- Listen. I have an idea.

526
00:45:16,590 --> 00:45:18,216
Sammy, I have an idea.

527
00:45:18,300 --> 00:45:20,969
<i>Just that his problem was mental, not physical.</i>

528
00:45:21,052 --> 00:45:24,306
I want you to have a pen in your pocket, okay?

529
00:45:24,389 --> 00:45:26,933
<i>- But she couldn't understand.</i>
- You're gonna have a pad in your pocket.

530
00:45:27,017 --> 00:45:29,019
- I did something wrong?
- You did something wrong!

531
00:45:29,102 --> 00:45:32,230
We're gonna deal with it.
We're gonna try harder.

532
00:45:32,314 --> 00:45:34,441
<i>She looks into his eyes
and sees the same person.</i>

533
00:45:34,524 --> 00:45:37,652
<i>If it's not a physical problem,
he should just snap out of it.</i>

534
00:45:37,736 --> 00:45:39,446
- Ellen called!
- Ellen called?

535
00:45:40,614 --> 00:45:44,159
- Ellen can't come today! Ellen can't come!
- Okay. I'm sorry!

536
00:45:44,242 --> 00:45:47,370
- I'm sorry. I'm trying. I'm sorry.
- Try harder!

537
00:45:51,124 --> 00:45:55,253
So good old Leonard Shelby from the insurance
company gives her the seed of doubt…

538
00:45:55,837 --> 00:45:57,964
just like he gave it to the doctors.

539
00:45:58,757 --> 00:46:01,468
But I never said that he was faking.
I never said that.

540
00:46:07,807 --> 00:46:10,185
I don't feel drunk.

541
00:47:22,382 --> 00:47:23,883
- Hello?
- Shit.

542
00:47:23,967 --> 00:47:25,385
Housekeeping.

543
00:47:25,468 --> 00:47:27,554
- Not right now.
- I'm sorry.

544
00:47:50,869 --> 00:47:51,745
Okay.

545
00:47:56,458 --> 00:48:00,587
“Dodd. Put him onto Teddy
or just get rid of him for Natalie.”

546
00:48:06,634 --> 00:48:07,761
Dodd.

547
00:48:12,932 --> 00:48:16,311
Get rid of him. Ask Natalie.

548
00:48:18,563 --> 00:48:19,814
Teddy, Teddy.

549
00:48:31,242 --> 00:48:33,495
<i>Leave your number.
You know what to do.</i>

550
00:48:33,578 --> 00:48:35,747
Yeah. This is a message for Teddy.

551
00:48:35,830 --> 00:48:37,874
I'm at the Mountcrest Inn
of Fifth Street, room six.

552
00:48:37,957 --> 00:48:40,960
I need you to come over
as soon as you get this. It's important.

553
00:48:41,044 --> 00:48:43,296
This is Leonard. Thanks. Bye.

554
00:48:47,592 --> 00:48:49,094
Fuck.

555
00:48:58,478 --> 00:49:02,148
What Mrs. Jankis didn't understand was
that you can't bully someone into remembering.

556
00:49:02,232 --> 00:49:04,234
The more pressure you're under,
the harder it gets.

557
00:49:06,986 --> 00:49:08,988
Then call me back?

558
00:49:30,927 --> 00:49:32,720
Okay. What am I doing?

559
00:49:35,056 --> 00:49:36,683
I'm chasing this guy.

560
00:49:39,269 --> 00:49:41,938
No. He's chasing me.

561
00:50:04,752 --> 00:50:06,379
Fuck.

562
00:50:09,799 --> 00:50:12,093
“Dodd. White guy.

563
00:50:12,177 --> 00:50:14,137
Mountcrest Inn on Fifth Street.”

564
00:50:15,096 --> 00:50:17,765
I'll get the jump on you, you fucker.

565
00:50:54,302 --> 00:50:55,762
Fuck.

566
00:50:58,431 --> 00:50:59,766
Sorry.

567
00:51:33,299 --> 00:51:35,301
I need a weapon.

568
00:51:38,554 --> 00:51:39,722
This'll do.

569
00:52:03,454 --> 00:52:05,811
I don't feel drunk.

570
00:52:47,915 --> 00:52:49,542
Do I know this guy?

571
00:52:51,002 --> 00:52:52,545
He seems to know me.

572
00:52:57,383 --> 00:52:58,801
What the fuck?

573
00:53:12,398 --> 00:53:14,567
- I like your car.
- Thank you.

574
00:53:14,650 --> 00:53:16,652
- Where'd you get it?
- Are you interested in buying one?

575
00:53:17,278 --> 00:53:19,197
I haven't made a strong enough
impression on you?

576
00:53:19,280 --> 00:53:21,282
I wouldn't be too hard on yourself.

577
00:53:32,001 --> 00:53:33,920
Okay. What am I doing?

578
00:53:44,597 --> 00:53:46,307
Who is this?

579
00:55:04,927 --> 00:55:06,846
Ouch. Cut it out.

580
00:55:38,628 --> 00:55:41,797
- How can you read that again?
- It's good.

581
00:55:43,049 --> 00:55:44,926
Yeah, but you've read it,
like, a thousand times.

582
00:55:45,009 --> 00:55:46,594
I enjoy it.

583
00:55:47,762 --> 00:55:50,598
I always thought the pleasure of a book
was in wanting to know what happens next.

584
00:55:50,681 --> 00:55:52,391
Don't be a prick.

585
00:55:52,475 --> 00:55:55,061
I'm not reading it to annoy you. I enjoy it.

586
00:55:56,187 --> 00:55:58,689
Just let me read, please.

587
00:56:09,534 --> 00:56:11,911
Probably tried this before.

588
00:56:14,038 --> 00:56:16,874
Probably burned truckloads of your stuff.

589
00:56:19,418 --> 00:56:21,420
Can't remember to forget you.

590
00:56:39,772 --> 00:56:40,815
Yeah.

591
00:56:41,399 --> 00:56:42,608
Uh-huh.

592
00:56:44,443 --> 00:56:47,571
Sir, that'd certainly be in keeping
with some of my own discoveries.

593
00:56:48,155 --> 00:56:51,534
I was hoping for a little more on the drugs angle.
Can you hang on a sec?

594
00:57:00,126 --> 00:57:03,379
The police report mentioned
the drugs found in the car outside my house.

595
00:57:03,462 --> 00:57:05,548
The car was stolen,
but his prints were all over it.

596
00:57:05,631 --> 00:57:08,342
I got friends in the department.
They gave me a copy of it.

597
00:57:08,426 --> 00:57:10,720
I dealt with the police a lot
in my insurance job.

598
00:57:10,803 --> 00:57:14,890
With my condition, it's really tough.
I can't keep it all in mind at once.

599
00:57:14,974 --> 00:57:18,227
I have to summarize the different sections.
And there's pages missing.

600
00:57:18,311 --> 00:57:20,479
I guess I've been trying to log them all.

601
00:57:20,563 --> 00:57:22,815
I don't know why these are crossed out.

602
00:57:22,898 --> 00:57:24,817
But they weren't even looking for John G.

603
00:57:24,900 --> 00:57:27,653
The stuff they found in the car fit in with
what they believed had happened…

604
00:57:27,737 --> 00:57:29,655
so they didn't chase any of it up.

605
00:58:05,775 --> 00:58:06,859
Honey.

606
00:58:09,362 --> 00:58:11,155
Honey, it's late.

607
00:58:33,386 --> 00:58:35,304
Everything okay?

608
00:58:52,947 --> 00:58:54,407
You okay in there?

609
00:58:57,910 --> 00:58:59,620
Was it good for you?

610
00:59:01,831 --> 00:59:04,750
What? Was I supposed to lock the door?

611
00:59:05,668 --> 00:59:06,752
No.

612
00:59:09,171 --> 00:59:11,090
I'd like you to leave now.

613
00:59:32,111 --> 00:59:35,156
There's something about the drugs stashed
in the car that doesn't ring true for me.

614
00:59:35,823 --> 00:59:37,742
Because the police claim
the guy was an addict…

615
00:59:37,825 --> 00:59:39,827
needing money to score,
which I think is bullshit…

616
00:59:39,910 --> 00:59:43,164
'cause he's not gonna go breaking into places
while he's still got a stash that big.

617
00:59:44,123 --> 00:59:46,792
I think John G. left it there
or planted it there.

618
00:59:48,627 --> 00:59:50,629
How do you know that?

619
00:59:52,089 --> 00:59:54,091
Shit. That's true. It fits.

620
00:59:54,800 --> 00:59:56,761
So he's a dealer.

621
00:59:57,428 --> 00:59:59,346
Hang on a sec.

622
01:00:09,482 --> 01:00:11,337
Now we're getting somewhere.

623
01:00:11,664 --> 01:00:13,152
“Discount Inn.”

624
01:01:07,122 --> 01:01:09,333
Yeah, okay. Blonde's fine.

625
01:01:11,710 --> 01:01:13,837
That's what they say.

626
01:01:13,921 --> 01:01:16,048
The Discount Inn. 304.

627
01:01:17,049 --> 01:01:18,092
Leonard.

628
01:01:19,510 --> 01:01:20,928
What then?

629
01:01:21,512 --> 01:01:24,223
We just go to bed.
You wait for me to fall asleep.

630
01:01:24,306 --> 01:01:26,392
You go into the bathroom and you slam the door.

631
01:01:26,475 --> 01:01:29,019
- Slam it?
- Yeah. Loud enough to wake me up.

632
01:01:29,103 --> 01:01:31,063
- And that's it?
- That's it.

633
01:01:33,858 --> 01:01:36,902
First I just need you to put
these things around the room.

634
01:01:39,947 --> 01:01:43,075
Just pretend they're your things
and that this is your bedroom.

635
01:01:54,878 --> 01:01:59,758
- Should I wear it?
- No. Just like you took it off or something.

636
01:02:02,720 --> 01:02:05,139
I don't want you to use it. I'm sorry.

637
01:02:06,849 --> 01:02:08,934
I just mean put them
around the room…

638
01:02:09,018 --> 01:02:11,604
as if they were your things.

639
01:02:16,108 --> 01:02:18,110
Whatever gets you off.

640
01:02:42,509 --> 01:02:44,637
I can't blame the cops
for not taking me seriously.

641
01:02:44,720 --> 01:02:47,056
This is a difficult condition
for people to understand.

642
01:02:47,139 --> 01:02:50,392
Look at Sammy Jankis.
His own wife couldn't deal with it.

643
01:02:50,476 --> 01:02:53,020
I told you about how she tried
to get him to snap out of it.

644
01:02:53,103 --> 01:02:56,440
Eventually she came to see me at the office.
I found out all kinds of shit.

645
01:02:56,941 --> 01:02:59,401
<i>She told me about life with Sammy,
how she treated him.</i>

646
01:02:59,485 --> 01:03:00,944
Thank you for seeing me.

647
01:03:01,028 --> 01:03:03,781
It got to the point where she'd get Sammy
to hide food all around the house.

648
01:03:03,864 --> 01:03:05,616
Then she'd stop feeding him
to see if his hunger…

649
01:03:05,699 --> 01:03:07,660
would make him remember
where he'd hidden the food.

650
01:03:09,995 --> 01:03:12,623
<i>She wasn't a cruel person.
She just wanted old Sammy back.</i>

651
01:03:12,706 --> 01:03:16,502
Mr. Shelby, you know all about Sammy
and you've decided that he's faking.

652
01:03:16,585 --> 01:03:19,213
Mrs. Jankis, the company's position
isn't that Sammy is faking anything…

653
01:03:19,296 --> 01:03:21,215
just that his condition can't be shown to be-

654
01:03:21,298 --> 01:03:24,760
I just want to know
what your honest opinion about Sammy is.

655
01:03:24,843 --> 01:03:27,763
We shouldn't even be talking like this
while the case is still open to appeal.

656
01:03:27,846 --> 01:03:31,100
- I'm not appealing the decision.
- Then why are you here?

657
01:03:31,183 --> 01:03:33,644
Try to understand.
When I look at Sammy…

658
01:03:33,727 --> 01:03:37,189
I don't see some… vegetable.

659
01:03:37,272 --> 01:03:39,358
I see my same old Sammy.

660
01:03:41,527 --> 01:03:45,948
What do you think that's like for me to suspect
he might be imagining this whole problem…

661
01:03:46,031 --> 01:03:48,117
and that if I just could say the right thing…

662
01:03:48,200 --> 01:03:50,994
he'd snap out of it
and go back to being normal?

663
01:03:56,542 --> 01:04:00,337
If I knew that my old Sammy were truly gone…

664
01:04:00,421 --> 01:04:04,550
then I could say good-bye
and start loving this new Sammy.

665
01:04:06,552 --> 01:04:09,388
As long as I have doubt,
I can't say good-bye and move on.

666
01:04:09,471 --> 01:04:11,223
What do you want from me?

667
01:04:11,306 --> 01:04:14,476
I want you to forget the company
you work for 30 seconds…

668
01:04:14,560 --> 01:04:18,230
and tell me if you really believe
that Sammy's faking his condition.

669
01:04:19,398 --> 01:04:23,485
I need to know… what you honestly believe.

670
01:04:28,824 --> 01:04:32,411
I believe that Sammy should be physically
capable of making new memories.

671
01:04:40,335 --> 01:04:41,420
Thank you.

672
01:04:44,089 --> 01:04:47,009
I thought I helped her. I thought
she just needed some kind of answer.

673
01:04:47,092 --> 01:04:49,094
I didn't think it was important
what the answer was…

674
01:04:49,928 --> 01:04:51,930
just that she had one to believe.

675
01:05:07,029 --> 01:05:09,865
- A car this nice you should lock.
- Who the fuck are you?

676
01:05:09,948 --> 01:05:12,284
- Teddy, your buddy.
- Prove it.

677
01:05:12,367 --> 01:05:15,996
Sammy. Remember Sammy?
You told me about Sammy!

678
01:05:17,539 --> 01:05:19,041
Geez!

679
01:05:19,124 --> 01:05:21,043
What the fuck are you doing in my car?

680
01:05:21,126 --> 01:05:23,253
What, your sense of humor went with the memory?

681
01:05:23,337 --> 01:05:26,298
- Do you even know why you're here?
- Unfinished business.

682
01:05:26,381 --> 01:05:28,759
Lenny, let me inform you.

683
01:05:28,842 --> 01:05:31,220
Your business here is very much finished.

684
01:05:31,303 --> 01:05:34,306
- You're still here because of Natalie.
- Who's Natalie?

685
01:05:34,389 --> 01:05:37,518
Schmuck, whose house do you think
you just walked out of?

686
01:05:39,895 --> 01:05:43,315
That's right. Take a look at your pictures.
I bet you got one of her.

687
01:05:45,234 --> 01:05:47,528
Nice shot, Leibovitz.

688
01:05:48,195 --> 01:05:51,365
You'll wanna make a note.
You can't trust her.

689
01:05:51,448 --> 01:05:52,825
Yeah? Why's that?

690
01:05:52,908 --> 01:05:56,161
Because by now she's taken
a look at this suit and the car…

691
01:05:56,245 --> 01:06:00,624
and she's starting to figure out ways
of turning the situation to her advantage.

692
01:06:01,583 --> 01:06:04,044
She's already got you staying
with her, for Christ's sakes.

693
01:06:04,127 --> 01:06:07,714
You can't go back in there.
Let me give you the name of a motel.

694
01:06:07,798 --> 01:06:11,677
- You're lucky I ran into you. That broad's bad news.
- What do you mean, “bad news”?

695
01:06:11,760 --> 01:06:14,054
She's involved with drugs.

696
01:06:14,138 --> 01:06:16,431
Look. These. You see these?

697
01:06:16,515 --> 01:06:18,475
This is the bar where she works.

698
01:06:18,559 --> 01:06:20,602
Her boyfriend's a drug dealer.

699
01:06:20,686 --> 01:06:23,313
She takes orders for him, arranges meets.

700
01:06:23,397 --> 01:06:26,275
He writes messages on the back of these.

701
01:06:26,358 --> 01:06:28,902
Then she slips him the answers
when she serves him his drinks.

702
01:06:28,986 --> 01:06:33,073
- Why should I care?
- Because when she gets jammed up…

703
01:06:33,156 --> 01:06:35,325
she's gonna use you to protect herself.

704
01:06:35,409 --> 01:06:36,618
From who?

705
01:06:36,702 --> 01:06:39,454
Guys are gonna wanna know
what happened to her boyfriend.

706
01:06:39,538 --> 01:06:43,083
Guys are gonna come after her.
Somebody's gotta pay, Lenny.

707
01:06:43,167 --> 01:06:46,211
Somebody always pays.
Maybe she'll make it you.

708
01:06:46,295 --> 01:06:49,798
Oh, yeah?
Maybe she'll make it you. Is that it?

709
01:06:49,882 --> 01:06:51,800
You worried that she's gonna use me against you?

710
01:06:51,884 --> 01:06:53,886
- No.
- Why not?

711
01:06:54,595 --> 01:06:57,222
Because she doesn't know who I am.

712
01:06:58,223 --> 01:07:00,767
- Why are you following me?
- Maybe I wanna help.

713
01:07:01,560 --> 01:07:04,771
She doesn't know anything about
your investigation, okay, Einstein?

714
01:07:04,855 --> 01:07:07,524
So write this down.

715
